reviews.review_text: Nevada Dead in the Godchaux era. Good quality soundboard except for mix on opening track "Promised Land" like the comment says.  According to GD database, this show had 3 sets.  2nd Set starts with China and 3rd set starts with Half-Step.

And They Call The Wind Irving I wrote a less than positive account of this concert years ago on one of the other sources and I would like to correct that now. On 5-12-20 I happened to catch TDIGDH and they were playing the Truckin' etc. jam and I was surprised how good it sounded. Having attended this show and been driven crazy by the wind, I thought they sucked and continued to feel that way for the last 46 years. No more. I've now listened to this particular Charlie Miller effort and I'm stunned at how good the show and the sound quality is. Even the vocals sound rich and warm, a rare occurrence in 74. I think the wind had everybody off kilter because Garcia thought they played "scrappy" too. Really appreciate this upgrade.

Made road-ready
This was their first of only two times in Reno (of 20 times in NV, 18 were in Vegas), though they had played just up the road, in a bowling alley at Tahoe Vista, in '68. They were coming from CBS Studios in San Francisco, where they had just finished tracking for Mars Hotel. The show is known for two things: the first with the complete touring Wall of Sound, and a landmark Truckin'. The Wall was accumulated in sections for shows in Feb, with the majority assembled for the March show. The U of NV Stadium date had been moved from the day before, and for the three days it took to learn to assemble the Wall, they were working around a track meet. The show went on through high winds, which swum the sound around the pitch all day. Witnesses described the crowd as mainly unresponsive newbies, compared to the usual scene, and that they too were nervous from the swaying PA. Billy talked about this show in his book - that the first time they flew the array directly over the drums riser was in the wind: "After a beta test at [Mar23] the Wall of Sound made its official debut in Reno. Fully assembled, the Wall measured something like forty feet high and almost eighty feet wide - super-cool to look at, but impossible to tame. Because the sound reinforcement was coming from a wall behind us—instead of a traditional PA off to the sides and in the front—the system had to use deferential mics in order to avoid feedback. In theory, it works. Technically, it works. But in actual use, it just sounds terrible...and it was utter madness. The Wall’s center cluster...We’re talking about two tons of speakers, suspended above the drums. As I walked to the stage that blustery day in Reno, the whole center section swayed significantly in the wind. Four thousand pounds, directly above my head. They were hung from one single winch and if something went wrong, I would be as flat as a penny on a railroad track. It never stopped being disconcerting to look up. But even beyond that, there were just too many problems. It was really hard to get with the sound. There was so much sound everywhere that the system wasn’t very accurate, and it frequently made things difficult for me." This show has detractors and fans. That's because it's average '74 fare until halfway. I think it compares well to any from the era, with Keith in particular having a great show. Because of the way earlier tapes were paused/cut and the nature of the setlist, a three-set list was arbitrarily construed. But now that we can hear the (mostly) compete tape, that's clearly incorrect (previously we had a left-channel AUD of the last third). It seems all patter is present, but there is no set-break note from Bobby. The longest break appears to be while fixing a speaker after Sugaree. It's clear there's no break after Rider, nor after Around, and after U.S. Blues Bobby tells Jer that Keith doesn't want to take a break (which he wouldn't need to say if they were that early in a second set). Throughout, no patter matches a break, and they stay onstage after Mississippi. The most logical break would be after Deal, because Bobby is (just barely) heard delivering an announcement from offstage; plus Tico was a common set-top tuning. But Phil's "those folks up on the hill - they got the right idea" would be a misfit comment as he was going offstage. The conclusion that fits: they were having fun playing with their massive new toy and gave one three-hour set. First Third. If you have ever been a soundman, you know that if you let musicians mix themselves onstage, they will keep turning themselves up louder than the others. That's one reason you need a mixer. Promised Land is a mess (granted, the SBD may not be what the AUD heard), and they cut short. 5mins in to Sugaree has the first sparks, but there are still issues (wind, OOT). Jer suddenly warms for Mexicali. A downtempo Tennessee is a bit off in places, but Jack Straw launches/solidifies proceedings. This is a notable Brown Eyed Women, with every player tighter than a stepdad's wallet. After Beat it on Down the Line-7, Phil makes a local joke about the high winds and greets someone from Maui. Jer is playful on the jam in a good China>Rider. Bobby starts a Feelin' Groovy just after 6mins. It takes a while to stick but then Jer flies. Middle Third. U.S. Blues is just the 4th one and Jer doesn't have the new lyrics down yet, but Keith sure is good. Jer goes on a brief-but-cool tour in a fine Greatest Story, Donnaskreech™ aside. Musta Been Roses is also the 4th one; this original, uptempo arrangement being the best. Me & Bobby McGee is exceptional - especially since '74 is not its best year. After a nice Deal there's a Tico-Tico no Fubá. The next couple are middling. Last Third. This Truckin' has received much attention. The verses are expertly delivered and the jam is highly entertaining. It has a sorta-Nobody's-Fault-like section after 7mins, while never quoting it directly. Eventually TOO is  a l m o s t  teased ... hinted at ... you can sense that's where Jer is going ... but they only cement back into Truckin'. It's another 6mins before Phil signals with the rumble - which he then has to play twice because the Truckin' dregs are just too sticky. In fact, 1min into this secondary/post-Truckin' thang, Phil teases TOO too, with a brief bass jam, where you can faintly hear a rumble-waiting Bobby (Jer?) prod him "go ahead!". We do get to The Other One, but Bobby is too far out to come back and remember the lyrics (that are burned into every DeadHead's mind) and completely flubs. Post verse, there's a full breakdown into a proto-Space, very E72-scented, with Billy on bells and whistles. They slowly return, but instead of the 2nd verse Bobby first teases Big River, then immediately begins driving a ¾-ton Mind Left Body. Jer puts on his slide and jumps right in the back, but he soon breaks it down and steers it to a Row Jimmy garage. Welcome back, hope you took photos. Bobby gets his Big River; worth the wait. Ship is the fifth one, but the first since the new intro was finished. It's also the first fully realized to completeness, and a slick performance. Bobby's fills and Keith's stentorian chords glaze it all together. The Sugar Mag is shaky as fuck, and there was no encore after they left the stage (they usually play another rather than end on a trainwreck). Phil thinks there will be, saying, "we'll see ya in a minute", whereas Jer says "this is like the Winter Olympics". Did he mean because this was an endurance event; because they were ready to run when the stacks toppled; because of the wind? Because why not the Summer Olympics? using old-school model: 1st third:  C+ 2nd third: B- 3rd third:  B+ Overall = 3½ stars [3¼ + ¼ for Truckin'] Highlights: Brown Eyed Women - every player on the dime's edge Me & Bobby McGee - rare '74 perfection Truckin' - into TOO; landmark Ship of Fools - the original type locality SOURCES: The 150221_sbd_miller is the most complete version, with fewer cuts and likely all tunings (there wasn't a Beer Barrel Polka). It does need pitch adjustment. It runs too fast at first, needing -2% for Promised>Mexicali; -1.5% for Jed & Jack; -1% for the rest. The matt_22248 source is also fast, replaces the Sugar Mag with one from 5/25 and adds a Beer Barrel tuning from the same date.
